Measurement Enclosure Light Conditions.CQ: what are the light conditions around the sample (closed or open space)

Instrument Model.Descriptive answer: model code (in old versions is not recorded in versions after 5 it is recorded under the path

Raman Light Source Runtime.CQ: How long has the light source been used? Hours of running?
Raman Light Source Runtime.Descriptive answer: A double value, possibly with unit of hours should be provided. After a certain number of running hours, the spectroscopic lamp reaches its half life and needs to be replaced. Not recorded (potentially ask Renishaw)

Raman Light Source Continuous Operation.CQ: How long has the light source been on constantly without being off? Also how long all the system has not been turned off?
Raman Light Source Continuous Operation.Descriptive answer: A double value in minutes should be provided denoting the continuous operation of the lamp prior to the test. this values is important, because it will help us to make a descsion if the internal calibration is valid. After the lamp is turned off and on calibration should be repeated. Also the lamp should be stabilised before the measurment some expert says that we need to keep it for 45 minutes at least

Internal Calibration Check.CQ: does the measurment performed on calibrated system?
Internal Calibration Check.Descriptive answer: compare when is the last time of each calibration and if each calibration has not expired. The internal calibration berformed and laser has not turned of. If it did not pass the lamp calibration should performed in the same session. The engineer and the lamp calibration have been done and has not expired (check their last record and their interval)

Date of last manufacturer calibration.CQ: Last time calibrated by manufacturer (engineer visit)?
Date of last manufacturer calibration.Descriptive answer: when is the last time we did calibration service for the instrument

Manufacturer Calibration Check.CQ: Did the instrument pass the internal/or external calibration (done by the user)?
Manufacturer Calibration Check.Descriptive answer: Instrument has an internal material that installed by the manufactrer. For everytime we want to use the instrument the user should run this internal calibration. The instrument will take a measurment of the silicon material and try to correct the detected intensity, the system has silicon for auto calibration, but you can use an external material such as polystyrene (intensity and position),silicon, sulphur  peak and width to the ideal silicon spectra. By doing so we reduce the systematic error coming from the detector. Note that other material might be used. Note that old devices insert the referance material maually. Note that it is important to identify the calibration material in case it contaminated/ruined as the instrument would keep fitting the calibration spectra with ideal spectra and apply correction

Calibration details.Value: wavelength 520.5 cm -1, intensity = few thousands, grating = 1200, laser = 785, DT, etc
Calibration details.CQ: Give me the full details about the calibration, peak location, peak intensity, laser used, grating … etc
Calibration details.Descriptive answer: Full data description of the calibration: follow up on the previous question, who did the calibration and when … etc

Internal Calibration Material.Value: Silicon, other infromation like batch number and grade are not available (not recorded)
Internal Calibration Material.CQ: What is the internal calibration material (full information, batch, name, formula, manufactring, expiry data etc)
Internal Calibration Material.Descriptive answer: see the previous question. This question is a follow up to check what is the material.

Offset Correction.CQ: if the internal calibration (by user) fail, did we do the offset correction?
Offset Correction.Descriptive answer: if the internal calibration fail, this means the instrument cannot do the automatic offset correction and require user intervention to do so.

Spatial Resolution.Descriptive answer: spatial resolution usually is defined by the optical properties of the system. Though sometimes in map scans it is expressed as the step used for acquiring the map.

Beam Coherence.CQ: how coherent does the beam hit the lense? (gaussian or non gaussian distribution (tophat)
Beam Coherence.Descriptive answer: For green and red lasers are gaussian profiles though the 830,785 and 1064 are line profile lasers. All have aberations.
